@Node "Requirements and Installation"

This software requires that you be running AmigaDOS(tm) 2.04 or higher.

Additionally, reqtools.library ( Copyright Nico François ) is used by UserTool. If you don't have reqtools.library, you can obtain it on any Aminet FTP site, or from my own Garshneblanker distribution.

To install UserTool, simply copy it to where you would like it to be located (the Tools directory being a popular choice). It can be run by double-clicking its icon or from the command line. No tooltypes or arguments are necessary or supported.

@EndNode

@Node "Using UserTool"

I've tried to make UserTool intuitive to use. I'll go over how to use its features and hopefully point out the non-intuitive nuances in the process.

First of all, you must be root to run UserTool, it will exit with a friendly requester if this is not the case.

When you start up UserTool, it will locate and read your passwd file and your MultiUser.group file automatically. It will inform you of any users who have empty passwords via a requester upon startup. Additionally, it will inform you of any invalidities in your passwd or group file and skip those lines. Note: if UserTool complains about a line, it is ignoring it, so when you save the passwd or group file later, it won't have that bad line in it. That line will be eliminated. (Of course, who would want bad lines in their passwd or group files?)

@{b}Creating a new user:@{ub}

When you click the "New" gadget below the Users listview, a new user will be inserted after the currently selected one. Their username will be "(new)" by default, and the text gadget below the Users listview will be activated. You can then simply delete the "(new)" and type in the user's actual username.

In addition, a few of the fields will automatically be filled in for you:

o The UserID field will automatically be filled with a number one higher than the highest UserID number in use (not including root who already has the highest possible UserID).

o The Home directory field will automatically be filled with the value of the DEFHOMEDIR environment variable. I put "SYS:Users/" in there so I only have to type the username when I create a new user. Additionally, if the directory in the Home directory field doesn't exist, UserTool will ask you if you want to create one with or without an icon (it will use the correct default directory as set by IconEdit as well).

o The Port (also called the Shell field) is ignored by MuFS, so I fill it with the default value of cli which seems to be the politically correct thing to put in there. In reality you can put whatever you like there, but I suspect that any sort of getty program for the Amiga might look at that field to figure out which shell to run when it logs someone in (of course none exist at the moment aside from one telnet daemon which automatically runs its own CON simulator anyhow, but I digress). 

You'll want to put the user's real name in the Real Name field (really?).

Finally, the Radio buttons signify whether or not the currently selected user is a member of the currently selected group (or the Manager, but there can only be one manager so UserTool will be a little more judicious about manager changes than membership changes). You'll want to select each group in turn and click "Member" if you wish the new user to become a member of that group.

That's about it for user creation.

@{b}Creating a new group:@{ub}

Creating a group is much like creating a user. A default name of "(new)" will be given. This name is called the GroupID by MuFS (as opposed to the GID which is the numerical identifier of the group). So, when you create a group, a requester will pop up asking you to enter a GID for this group. There will be a default value of one higher than the highest GID currently in your group file. Also, another requester will pop up asking for the group name. This can be whatever you like and won't really appear anywhere (so "Bob's Cool New Group" would be a perfectly reasonable value). The GroupID will be what shows up in directory listings and the like.

By default the user currently selected will be made the manager of this group. You can of course change this by simply selecting a different user and clicking on the "Manager" radio button.

Also, all users will default to "Non-member"s which is intuitive if you think about the structure of the MultiUser.group file.

That's it for group creation.

@{b}Changing passwords, etc:@{ub}

The last thing to make note of is the "Change Password" button. UserTool keeps all changes in memory and doesn't generate a new password file until you select "Save", however, in order to maintain integrity with the multiuser.library, the password file must be saved before a password change can be made. So, if the password file has been modified, the "Change Password" button will pop up a requester asking you if it can save the password file before changing the password.

Also, note that your old passwd and MultiUser.group files are moved to passwd.bak and MultiUser.group.bak (and any pre-existing .bak files are deleted). I have put a great deal of effort in making sure that the passwd file and group file are always somewhere in some form and never "accidentally" destroyed.

@EndNode

